# TODO — Navi

WhatsApp-native AI assistant for notes, TODOs, reminders, scheduling, and social coordination.
Named after Link's fairy companion in The Legend of Zelda — the one who never lets you forget.

## Tech Stack

- **Backend**: Laravel 12 (PHP 8.4) — API, business logic, queue jobs, user/billing data
- **WhatsApp Integration**: WhatsApp Business API (official Meta REST API) — webhook-based, multi-tenant, no Node.js bridge needed. Pure HTTP: Meta POSTs incoming messages to Laravel webhook controller, Laravel responds via Meta's Send Message API. Per-conversation cost ~$0.005-0.08 depending on region/type.
- **Context Database**: OpenViking — memory extraction (8 categories), semantic search, hierarchical retrieval (L0/L1/L2), social context graph
- **Primary LLM**: MiniMax M2.5 ($0.118/$0.99 per MTok) — S-tier tool calling (SWE-bench 80.2%), text-only, OpenAI SDK-compatible. Handles all user-facing conversation AND OpenViking VLM operations (memory extraction, dedup, L0/L1 generation, merging). Automatic caching built in.
- **STT**: Groq Whisper Large v3 Turbo ($0.04/hr) — WhatsApp voice note transcription. 216x realtime speed (<0.2s for a 30-second note). Transcripts fed to MiniMax as text. Decouples audio from LLM choice for provider agnosticism.
- **Image Processing**: GLM-4.7-Flash (free, $0.07/$0.40 paid) — One-shot image-to-text descriptions. Images described in Laravel before entering OpenViking, so OpenViking and MiniMax only ever see text. Fallback: Gemini 2.5 Flash-Lite or GPT-4.1-nano ($0.10/$0.40).
- **Relational Database**: PostgreSQL — users, subscriptions, audit logs, billing, system config
- **Cache/Queue**: Redis — job queue, rate limiting, session caching

### Database Architecture Decision

PostgreSQL + OpenViking (dual-database strategy):
- **PostgreSQL** handles structured relational data: user accounts, subscriptions, billing records, API usage tracking, system configuration. Standard Laravel Eloquent models.
- **OpenViking** handles the context layer: user memories (profile, preferences, entities, events, cases, patterns), conversation sessions, knowledge resources, and the social coordination graph. Its 8-category automatic memory extraction maps directly to the app's core value — understanding users deeply over time. The L0/L1/L2 hierarchical information model (abstract ~100 tokens → overview ~2K tokens → full detail) minimizes LLM token consumption during retrieval. Relations API models edges in the social graph (who coordinates with whom, about what, how frequently).
- No separate graph database needed. OpenViking's relations + semantic search cover graph traversal and context-aware queries. PostgreSQL covers everything that needs ACID transactions and traditional indexing.

### WhatsApp Business API Integration Path

Laravel receives incoming messages via Meta's webhook (POST to a verified endpoint). Message flow: User sends WhatsApp message → Meta delivers webhook payload (JSON) to Laravel → `WhatsAppWebhookController` validates signature (HMAC-SHA256 with app secret) → dispatches `ProcessMessageJob` → job processes through OpenViking/MiniMax pipeline → response sent back via `POST https://graph.facebook.com/v22.0/{phone_number_id}/messages`. Media (images, audio, documents) downloaded from Meta's CDN URLs included in webhook payload. No Baileys, no Node.js bridge, no OpenClaw — pure Laravel HTTP.

Setup: register Meta Business account → create WhatsApp Business app in Meta Developer Console → configure webhook URL + verify token → obtain permanent access token → set up phone number. For proactive messages (reminders, digests) outside the 24-hour window, use pre-approved Message Templates (utility category).

**Meta 2026 chatbot policy risk:** Meta's January 2026 ToS update bans "general-purpose AI chatbots." Navi should be positioned during business verification as a "structured productivity assistant" (TODO management, calendar scheduling, reminders, note-taking) — not an open-ended conversational AI. Feature set supports this framing. Legal review recommended before production launch.

### OpenViking Integration Path

Laravel communicates with OpenViking via its REST API (`http://localhost:1933`). Key operations: session creation, message recording, memory commit (triggers automatic extraction), semantic search, resource management, relation linking. No native PHP SDK exists — use Laravel HTTP facade with a thin service wrapper. Multi-tenant support built into OpenViking maps to per-user context isolation. VLM provider: MiniMax M2.5 (via LiteLLM, OpenAI-compatible). Images are described in Laravel (GLM-4.7-Flash) and enter OpenViking as text — MiniMax never sees raw images.

### Model Strategy Rationale

Provider agnosticism is a core architectural goal. Binding to a single provider's native multimodal capabilities (e.g., Gemini's audio input) creates lock-in. Instead, modalities are decoupled into independent processing layers:
- **Audio**: Groq Whisper transcribes → text enters LLM. Any text model works as primary.
- **Images**: GLM-4.7-Flash describes → text enters OpenViking. LLM and image model are independently swappable.
- **Text + tool calling**: MiniMax M2.5. Can be swapped for Qwen3.5 Plus, Kimi K2.5, or GLM-4.7 without touching audio/image pipelines.
- **Background ops**: Same MiniMax M2.5 instance for OpenViking VLM. Quality matters here — write-once, read-many operations (memory extraction, dedup, L0/L1 generation) permanently shape the user's context model. Cheap-but-dumb models (Doubao Mini, Gemini Flash-Lite) are inadequate.

Each layer is a `ProviderInterface` implementation, independently configurable and swappable.

### OpenViking Internals & Design Constraints

Findings from deep-dive into OpenViking source code and documentation (2026-04-05). These constraints shape architectural decisions throughout the project.

**Session commit is two-phase and client-triggered:**
- Phase 1 (sync): archives current messages to `history/archive_NNN/`, clears live message list, returns `task_id`.
- Phase 2 (async background): generates L0/L1 summaries for the archive, calls `SessionCompressor.extract_long_term_memories()` for 8-category extraction, creates bidirectional relations between memories and referenced resources/skills, writes `.done` marker.
- There is no automatic commit trigger. `auto_commit_threshold` (default 8000) exists as a constructor hint, but the client must explicitly call `commit()`. **We must build commit orchestration in Laravel.**

**Deduplication is two-stage (vector pre-filter → LLM decision):**
- Stage 1: candidate memory is embedded, vector search returns up to 5 similar existing memories from the same category. Similarity threshold is hardcoded at 0.0 (returns anything the vector index finds).
- Stage 2: if similar memories found, candidate + existing memories are sent to the VLM (temperature 0.0) for a decision: `skip` (duplicate), `create` (new, optionally deleting conflicting existing), or `none` (don't create, but merge/delete existing). Merge is preferred over delete for partial conflicts.
- Triggered on every commit, for every candidate extracted (except `profile` which always merges, and `tools`/`skills` which use special logic).
- **Not configurable.** Thresholds and max-similar-count are hardcoded. Dedup prompt template is theoretically customizable but not exposed via config.

**8 memory categories and their mutability:**
- User-scoped: `profile` (single file, always merge), `preferences` (mergeable), `entities` (mergeable), `events` (immutable — append-only).
- Agent-scoped: `cases` (immutable), `patterns` (mergeable), `tools` (special merge), `skills` (special merge).
- Conflict resolution: LLM decides per-memory. Partial conflict → merge both into unified memory with regenerated L0/L1/L2. Full invalidation → delete old + create new.

**Session context retrieval (`get_session_context`) has a token budget:**
- Default 128K tokens. Budget applies to archive content only — live (unarchived) messages are always included.
- Priority: latest archive L1 (overview) first, then older archive L0s (abstracts) newest-first until budget exhausted.
- Older abstracts are dropped first. Stats returned include `droppedArchives` count.
- **We must tune this per-call** since Navi's LLM prompts also need room for: system prompt, retrieved memories, retrieved resources, user query, and response generation.

**Relations carry no numeric weight:**
- Relations store a `reason` string and nothing else. No frequency counts, reliability scores, or typed metadata.
- Relations do participate in retrieval (up to `MAX_RELATIONS = 5` followed per resource).
- Auto-generated on commit (memory ↔ resource/skill links). Also manually creatable via API.
- **For the coordination graph moat, we need a supplementary metrics layer in PostgreSQL.**

**Gaps we must fill (OpenViking does not provide):**
1. Session commit orchestration — when and how often to trigger commits for always-on WhatsApp conversations.
2. Archive retention — archives accumulate indefinitely with no cleanup policy.
3. Resource compaction — notes/documents never auto-merge or synthesize.
4. Group chat session modeling — sessions are single-user scoped; no native multi-user session concept.
5. Coordination graph quantitative metrics — relations lack weights for frequency/reliability tracking.
6. Commit cost accounting — each commit triggers multiple LLM + embedding calls; cost scales linearly with users.

---

## Tier 0 — Foundation & Infrastructure

1. **Project scaffolding** — Initialize Laravel 12 project in `api/` directory. Docker Compose with services: app (Laravel FPM + Nginx), pgsql (PostgreSQL 18), redis (Redis 7), openviking (context DB). Multi-stage Dockerfile (base → dev → production). `.env.example` with all service connection vars. PER code style via Laravel Pint (`pint.json`). Pest testing framework. Match breakthrough project's directory structure and naming conventions exactly.

2. **Git & CI infrastructure** — Conventional commits via commitlint + Husky (root-level `package.json`, `commitlint.config.mjs`, `.gitmessage` template). GitHub Actions CI pipeline: backend-lint, backend-test, dependency-audit. `.gitignore` for OS, IDE, Claude Code, node_modules, vendor, .env files.

3. **WhatsApp Business API setup** — Register Meta Business account, create WhatsApp Business app in Meta Developer Console. Configure webhook endpoint in Laravel (`POST /api/webhook/whatsapp`) with HMAC-SHA256 signature verification. Obtain permanent access token (System User token, not short-lived). Register phone number. Build `App\Http\Controllers\WhatsAppWebhookController` (receives messages) and `App\Services\WhatsAppService` (sends messages via Graph API). Handle text, images, audio, video, documents, locations, contacts. Set up Meta's test number for local development (free, no business verification needed). Configure Message Templates for proactive messages (reminders, daily digests) — utility category templates auto-approve within minutes.

4. **OpenViking deployment & Laravel integration** — Deploy OpenViking as Docker service (HTTP server mode, port 1933). Create Laravel service class (`App\Services\OpenVikingService`) wrapping REST API calls. Configure VLM provider: MiniMax M2.5 via LiteLLM (OpenAI-compatible endpoint). Configure embedding provider (Jina, Voyage, or MiniMax if available). Verify: create session → add message → commit → memory extracted with correct VLM.

5. **WhatsApp message pipeline** — Build the end-to-end message flow: Meta webhook delivers message → `WhatsAppWebhookController` validates + extracts payload → dispatches `ProcessMessageJob` to Redis queue → job identifies user (phone number → `users` table), routes by media type (text/audio/image/document), processes through STT/image/OpenViking/MiniMax pipeline → `WhatsAppService::sendMessage()` sends response back via Graph API. Handle delivery status webhooks (sent, delivered, read). Media downloads via Meta CDN URLs (time-limited, must download promptly). Implement retry logic for failed sends (Meta rate limits: 80 messages/second for Business API tier).

5a. **Zero-friction user registration** — No signup form, no onboarding gate. First message from an unknown phone number auto-creates a `users` record (phone number, country code, created_at). User is immediately active. Further profile data (email, name, timezone override, Google Calendar) is collected progressively as the user engages features that require it ("connect my calendar" → OAuth flow, "email this to Juan" → "what's your email address?"). Timezone inferred from phone country code on registration (covers single-timezone countries reliably — Colombia +57 → America/Bogota, Spain +34 → Europe/Madrid). Multi-timezone countries (US, Brazil, Russia) get a reasonable default; user can override ("set my timezone to EST"). **Critical rule:** inferred timezone is only a provisional default. Any time-sensitive action (reminders, events, schedule-aware digests, conflict detection) must check whether the timezone has been explicitly confirmed by the user. If not, Navi opens a `timezone_confirmation` pending-action flow and asks for confirmation before relying on that timezone for scheduling.

5b. **Webhook idempotency** — Meta retries failed webhook deliveries up to 7 times over 72 hours. Without deduplication, the same message processes multiple times (duplicate TODOs, double LLM costs). Store each `message_id` from the webhook payload in Redis (`SETNX` with 72-hour TTL). If the key already exists, acknowledge the webhook (200 OK) but skip processing. Check happens in `WhatsAppWebhookController` before job dispatch, not in the job itself.

5c. **Per-user job serialization** — User sends 3 messages in rapid succession → 3 `ProcessMessageJob` instances dispatch simultaneously. Without serialization, all three read/write the same OpenViking session concurrently, causing race conditions (message ordering, context corruption). Use Laravel's `WithoutOverlapping` job middleware keyed on `user_id` — jobs for the same user queue sequentially, different users process in parallel. Combined with Redis lock (match breakthrough's queue patterns).

6. **Baseline database schema design** — Design the core PostgreSQL schema before the first migration runs. Tier 0/1 tables: `users` (phone_number, country_code, timezone, email nullable, name nullable, tier, created_at), `user_whatsapp_sessions` (user_id, openviking_session_id, last_committed_at), `session_commits` (session_id, archive_index, status, started_at, completed_at), `api_usage_records` (user_id, operation_type, model, input_tokens, output_tokens, cost_cents, created_at), `audit_logs` (event_type, user_id, metadata_json, created_at). Tier 2 tables (design now, migrate when needed): `todos`, `reminders`, `events`, `notes`. Tier 3 tables: `delegations`, `coordination_edges`. Use Laravel migrations with conventional naming. Design indexes for the queries we know we'll run (user lookups by phone_number, todos by user_id + status, reminders by fire_at, usage records by user_id + created_at). This is a living design — but getting the core right prevents retroactive migrations.

6i. **User understanding schema** — Define Navi's long-term personalization model as a standalone spec in `USER_UNDERSTANDING_SCHEMA.md`. This schema governs what durable user understanding belongs in OpenViking (preferences, patterns, commitments, entities, constraints, goals, knowledge resources) and what stays canonical in PostgreSQL. Treat it as the contract for long-term memory extraction, freshness, confidence, and capability-specific personalization.

6j. **Pending action state model** — Add a first-class PostgreSQL table for in-progress user workflows so the app does not rely on raw conversation history to resolve replies like "yes", "send it", or "move it to tomorrow". Proposed schema:
- `pending_actions`
- Core columns: `id`, `user_id`, `action_type`, `status`, `priority`, `requires_confirmation`, `current_step`, `draft_payload_json`, `context_summary`, `origin_message_id`, `last_user_message_id`, `expires_at`, `resolved_at`, `cancelled_at`, `created_at`, `updated_at`
- Optional coordination columns: `parent_action_id`, `related_entity_type`, `related_entity_id`, `tool_name`, `confirmation_token`
- Recommended enums:
  `action_type`: `reminder_draft`, `event_draft`, `email_draft`, `todo_clarification`, `delegation_request`, `timezone_confirmation`
  `status`: `open`, `awaiting_user`, `awaiting_system`, `confirmed`, `completed`, `cancelled`, `expired`
- Indexes: `(user_id, status)`, `(user_id, action_type, status)`, `(expires_at)`, `(origin_message_id)`
- Rule: PostgreSQL is canonical. The LLM may read a rendered summary of pending actions, but it does not own them.

6k. **Operational entity schemas** — Formalize canonical PostgreSQL schemas for `todos`, `reminders`, and `events` before implementation:
- `todos`: `id`, `user_id`, `list_name`, `title`, `notes`, `status`, `priority`, `due_at`, `completed_at`, `source_message_id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`
- `reminders`: `id`, `user_id`, `title`, `body`, `scheduled_for`, `timezone`, `status`, `delivery_channel`, `recurrence_rule`, `snooze_until`, `source_message_id`, `fired_at`, `created_at`, `updated_at`
- `events`: `id`, `user_id`, `title`, `description`, `starts_at`, `ends_at`, `timezone`, `location`, `status`, `participants_json`, `external_calendar_id`, `external_event_id`, `source_message_id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`
- Recommended enums:
  `todos.status`: `open`, `completed`, `cancelled`
  `todos.priority`: `low`, `medium`, `high`
  `reminders.status`: `scheduled`, `queued`, `fired`, `cancelled`, `failed`
  `events.status`: `draft`, `confirmed`, `cancelled`
- Indexes:
  `todos`: `(user_id, status, due_at)`, `(user_id, list_name, status)`
  `reminders`: `(status, scheduled_for)`, `(user_id, status, scheduled_for)`
  `events`: `(user_id, starts_at)`, `(external_calendar_id, external_event_id)`

6m. **Notes schema** — Formalize a lightweight canonical PostgreSQL schema for notes while preserving OpenViking as the primary retrieval/context layer. Proposed schema:
- `notes`: `id`, `user_id`, `title`, `source_type`, `status`, `body_text`, `summary`, `tag_list_json`, `original_file_path`, `mime_type`, `captured_at`, `source_message_id`, `openviking_resource_id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`
- Recommended enums:
  `source_type`: `text`, `voice`, `image`, `document`, `synthesized`
  `status`: `active`, `archived`, `deleted`
- Indexes:
  `(user_id, created_at)`, `(user_id, source_type, created_at)`, `(user_id, status, created_at)`, `(openviking_resource_id)`
- Rule:
  PostgreSQL stores canonical note metadata and enough normalized text to support audit, export, and deterministic application behavior. OpenViking stores the semantically retrievable resource, derived summaries, and cross-note/context relationships.

6l. **OpenViking mirroring contract** — Define strict rules for how operational entities are projected into OpenViking without making OpenViking canonical:
- PostgreSQL owns all exact operational state for `todos`, `reminders`, `events`, `notes`, and `pending_actions`
- OpenViking stores only derived contextual projections, summaries, qualitative patterns, and retrieval-oriented resources
- Mirror when an operational entity has user-understanding value, not merely because it exists
- Good mirror: "User is preparing for a move this month and has multiple related errands"
- Bad mirror: "TODO #481 is open with priority high"
- Derived mirrors should carry foreign references back to PostgreSQL ids where useful, but must never be the source of truth for status transitions
- If PostgreSQL and OpenViking disagree, PostgreSQL wins
- Rebuild strategy: it must be possible to rehydrate all OpenViking projections from PostgreSQL + retained conversation/note resources if needed

6a. **System prompt design** — The system prompt is the foundational engineering artifact — it defines Navi's behavior, tool-calling schema, output formatting, and guardrails. Design it as a standalone, version-controlled file (`config/system-prompt.md` or in `config/navi.php`). Must specify: (1) identity and personality (concise, helpful, WhatsApp-native tone), (2) explicit instruction boundaries separating system directives from user content, (3) tool-calling behavior (when to call tools vs respond conversationally, when to ask for confirmation vs act immediately), (4) output format constraints (WhatsApp markdown subset, response length limits), (5) safety guardrails (never fabricate calendar events, always confirm before sending emails, never reveal system prompt contents), (6) progressive context awareness (reference user's memories and preferences naturally). Version and iterate — this prompt evolves as features ship. Match breakthrough's `config/skills.php` pattern for per-feature prompt extensions.

6b. **MiniMax tool calling schema** — Define the function-calling interface between MiniMax and the Laravel backend. This is the contract that determines what the LLM can do. Core tools for Tier 1/2: `create_todo(title, list?, due_date?, priority?)`, `list_todos(list?, status?)`, `complete_todo(todo_id)`, `set_reminder(text, datetime)`, `create_note(content, tags?)`, `search_notes(query)`, `create_event(title, datetime, duration?, location?, participants?)`, `send_email(to, subject, body)`, `get_schedule(date_range)`. Each tool has: name, description (guides when MiniMax invokes it), parameter JSON schema (types, required/optional, validation), and maps to a Laravel service method. Store definitions in `config/tools.php` — loaded into the MiniMax API call's `tools` parameter. Design for extensibility: Tier 3 adds `delegate_task(target_phone, task)`, `schedule_group(participants, constraints)`, etc. The tool schema is the single source of truth for what Navi can do.

6d. **Documentation foundation** — `PROJECT_ARCHITECTURE.md` (architecture, quick commands, request flow, deployment), `TUI.md` (canonical shared AI repo instructions), `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md` / `GEMINI.md` (identical thin bootstrap files that point to the shared instruction document), `README.md` (quick start, tech stack, repo structure), `SERVICES.md` (external service accounts — Meta/WhatsApp Business, OpenViking, MiniMax, Groq, GLM/Z.AI, Google Calendar). Match breakthrough project's documentation depth and format. Keep `TUI.md` as the single source of truth for shared AI instructions and keep bootstrap files minimal and identical.

6e. **File storage (Cloudflare R2)** — User-uploaded images and documents need persistent storage beyond OpenViking's text representations. Cloudflare R2: S3-compatible API (Laravel's `s3` filesystem driver works out of the box), zero egress fees, free tier 10GB + 10M reads/month, $0.015/GB after. Configure in `.env` (`R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID`, `R2_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY`, `R2_BUCKET`, `R2_ENDPOINT`). File path structure: `users/{user_id}/{type}/{uuid}.{ext}`. OpenViking resources reference R2 paths for retrieval. No AWS account needed — R2 is Cloudflare-native.

6f. **Deployment (Render)** — Match breakthrough's Render topology. Services: `navi-api` (Web Service, Docker), `navi-worker` (Background Worker, Docker), `navi-db` (Managed PostgreSQL), `navi-redis` (Managed Redis), `navi-openviking` (Web Service or Background Worker, Docker). Shared env group for secrets across api/worker/openviking. Meta webhook URL: `https://api.{domain}/api/webhook/whatsapp`. Auto-deploy from `main` branch. Migrations on api startup (`RUN_MIGRATIONS=true`).

6g. **OpenViking backup strategy** — OpenViking stores the most valuable data in the system (user memories, social coordination graph). Render managed PostgreSQL has automatic daily backups. OpenViking runs on a Docker volume with no built-in backup. Strategy: (1) scheduled daily export of OpenViking data via its `.ovpack` export API to Cloudflare R2, (2) Render persistent disk for the OpenViking Docker volume (survives deploys), (3) weekly verification that exports are restorable. Track backup status in PostgreSQL. Alert on failed backups. RPO: 24 hours (matching breakthrough's PostgreSQL RPO).

6h. **OpenViking commit cost model** — Each OpenViking session commit triggers: 1 LLM extraction call (all archived messages → 8-category memory candidates), N dedup calls (one per candidate × up to 5 similar memories each, so potentially 1 vector search + 1 LLM call per candidate), embedding calls for new/merged memories, and L0/L1 generation for the archive. VLM provider: MiniMax M2.5 ($0.118/$0.99 per MTok) — chosen for quality over cheapness because these write-once, read-many operations permanently shape the user's context model. At scale (1000 DAU, 1 commit/day): ~1000 extraction calls + ~5000-8000 dedup calls = ~$1.40/day (~$42/month). Modest cost for S-tier quality on the operations that define the product's intelligence. Build cost tracking into `api_usage_records` from day one (match breakthrough's `operation_type` pattern: `'memory_extraction'`, `'memory_dedup'`, `'archive_summary'`, `'image_description'`, `'audio_transcription'`). Set per-user commit frequency caps as a cost lever.

6n. **Open questions to resolve before implementation** — Capture still-open architectural choices explicitly so they do not remain buried in prose:
- Choose the embedding provider for OpenViking (`Jina`, `Voyage`, `MiniMax`, or other) based on quality, latency, and PHP/LiteLLM integration ergonomics.
- Decide the exact Meta Message Template strategy for reminders, digests, and other proactive sends outside the 24-hour window.
- Decide whether `navi-worker` also runs the scheduler or whether scheduler execution should be split into a separate dedicated process/service.
- Define exact OpenViking commit thresholds and escalation rules: standard message-count threshold, end-of-day cutoff, burst-chat behavior, and whether high-impact actions force an immediate commit.
- Define the exact rebuild/export procedure for OpenViking projections so a full rehydration from PostgreSQL + retained resources is operationally tested, not merely intended.

## Tier 0.5 — Security & Hardening

7s. **Webhook signature verification** — Every incoming Meta webhook request must be validated via HMAC-SHA256 using the app secret before processing. Reject unsigned/invalid payloads immediately. This is the front door to the entire system — a forged webhook means attacker-controlled messages entering the LLM pipeline. Implement in `WhatsAppWebhookController` middleware, matching breakthrough's auth middleware pattern.

8s. **Secrets management** — API keys (MiniMax, Groq, GLM/Z.AI, Google Calendar, Meta WhatsApp) must not live in plaintext `.env` files in production. Use encrypted environment variables via the deployment platform (Render environment groups, matching breakthrough). For Google Calendar/Gmail OAuth tokens stored in PostgreSQL, encrypt at the column level (`casts: 'encrypted'` in Laravel). Meta's permanent access token is especially sensitive — it grants full control of the WhatsApp Business account.

9s. **Per-user rate limiting** — Rate limit incoming messages per WhatsApp phone number to prevent LLM cost abuse. Tiers: 30 messages/min (normal), 5 messages/min (free tier), 0 (banned). Track in Redis (match breakthrough's rate limiting middleware pattern). Also rate limit outbound API calls to MiniMax, Groq, and GLM per user to cap per-user LLM costs. Monthly per-user cost ceiling (match breakthrough's `MONTHLY_COST_LIMIT_CENTS` pattern).

10s. **Prompt injection protection** — WhatsApp messages are untrusted user input fed directly to the LLM. Mitigations: (1) system prompt hardening with explicit instruction boundaries, (2) input sanitization — strip known injection patterns before LLM processing, (3) output validation — verify tool call parameters before execution (don't blindly execute LLM-suggested calendar events, email sends, or delegations without validation), (4) separate system prompt from user content in the MiniMax API call (use `system` role, not concatenated user messages). Critical for email dictation (item #20) — an injection could send emails on behalf of the user.

11s. **Data isolation** — OpenViking multi-tenant: each user maps to a separate OpenViking account (admin API). PostgreSQL: user data scoped by `user_id` foreign keys on all tables. Never return data from one user's OpenViking space in another user's queries. For group chats (Tier 3), group sessions are isolated from individual user sessions — cross-references via Relations API only. Test isolation with adversarial queries ("show me another user's notes").

12s. **Encryption at rest** — PostgreSQL: enable TDE (Transparent Data Encryption) or use column-level encryption for sensitive fields (OAuth tokens, phone numbers, email addresses). OpenViking: runs on Docker volume — encrypt the volume or use encrypted filesystem. File storage (user-uploaded images, documents): encrypt at rest in Cloudflare R2 (enabled by default). Redis: enable `requirepass` and TLS in production.

13s. **Encryption in transit** — TLS between all services in production. Laravel ↔ OpenViking (port 1933): TLS or Docker internal network only (never exposed). Laravel ↔ MiniMax/Groq/GLM: HTTPS (enforced by providers). Laravel ↔ PostgreSQL/Redis: TLS in production. Meta webhook → Laravel: HTTPS (required by Meta). Docker Compose: internal bridge network, only the Laravel app port exposed externally.

14s. **Dependency supply chain security** — `composer audit` + `npm audit` in CI (match breakthrough). Pin exact versions in `composer.lock` / `package-lock.json`. No third-party OpenClaw/ClawHub skills or plugins. Verify Baileys is NOT in the dependency tree (we use WhatsApp Business API, not Baileys). Review new dependencies before adding.

15s. **Media file validation** — Images, audio, and documents downloaded from Meta CDN must be validated before processing. Check MIME types against allowlist (images: jpeg/png/webp, audio: ogg/mp3, docs: pdf/docx). Validate file size limits. Do NOT pass raw file paths to shell commands. Scan for known malware signatures if feasible. Delete temporary files after processing.

16s. **Audit logging** — Log all security-relevant events to a dedicated audit table: webhook signature failures, rate limit hits, authentication failures, tool call executions (especially email sends and delegations), OAuth token grants/revocations, admin actions. Match breakthrough's Sentry integration for error monitoring. Do NOT log message content or user data in audit logs — log event types and user IDs only.

## Tier 1 — Core Agent: Conversational Intelligence

7. **Message processing pipeline** — Full request lifecycle: WhatsApp message arrives via Meta webhook → Laravel dispatches `ProcessMessageJob` → job creates/resumes OpenViking session → records message → retrieves relevant context (memories, resources) via semantic search → constructs LLM prompt with context → sends to MiniMax M2.5 → response sent back via WhatsApp Business API (`WhatsAppService::sendMessage()`). Handle graceful failures at each step. Job-based processing via Redis queue (match breakthrough's `ProcessMessageJob` pattern).

8. **Multi-modal input processing** — All modalities converge into text before hitting MiniMax or OpenViking. **Text**: direct to MiniMax. **Audio**: WhatsApp voice notes arrive as `.ogg` files (downloaded from Meta CDN URL in webhook payload) → Laravel sends to Groq Whisper Large v3 Turbo API → transcript returned in <0.2s → transcript processed as text by MiniMax. Build `App\Services\TranscriptionService` wrapping Groq API. **Images**: downloaded from Meta CDN → Laravel sends to GLM-4.7-Flash API → text description returned → original file stored (Cloudflare R2) → text description + file path reference sent to OpenViking as a resource → OpenViking generates L0/L1/L2 from text via MiniMax. Build `App\Services\ImageDescriptionService` wrapping GLM API. **Documents**: PDF/DOCX downloaded from Meta CDN → ingested into OpenViking with its built-in document parser (handles PDF/MD/HTML/DOCX natively). All services implement `ProviderInterface` for swappability.

9. **Session commit orchestration** — OpenViking sessions map 1:1 with WhatsApp DM conversations (per-user = one long-running session). Since OpenViking does not auto-commit, Laravel must own the trigger logic. Build `SessionCommitService` that commits based on a hybrid policy: whichever fires first of (a) message count threshold (e.g., every 15-20 messages) or (b) time window (e.g., end-of-day for the user's timezone). Commits are async (Phase 1 archives instantly, Phase 2 extracts memories in background) — track commit status in PostgreSQL (`session_commits` table: session_id, archive_index, status, started_at, completed_at) and handle Phase 2 failures with retry logic. Tune `get_session_context()` token budget per-call: subtract system prompt + retrieved memories + resource tokens from the model's context window, pass remainder as budget. Laravel tracks session mappings in PostgreSQL (`user_whatsapp_sessions` table).

9a. **Archive retention policy** — OpenViking archives accumulate indefinitely. Design a retention policy: after memories are extracted and Phase 2 completes successfully, archives older than a configurable threshold (e.g., 90 days) can be pruned — their value has been captured in extracted memories. However, L0 abstracts of pruned archives should be preserved (copied to a `pruned_abstracts` resource) so the agent retains awareness that those conversations happened, just without detail. Implement as a scheduled Laravel job (`PruneSessionArchivesJob`). Must never prune archives whose Phase 2 hasn't completed. Track pruning in PostgreSQL for audit.

10. **Conversational UX foundations** — Natural language understanding for intent detection (the user says "remind me" vs "note this down" vs "schedule a meeting" vs just chatting). System prompt engineering for Navi's personality: helpful, concise, proactive but not annoying. WhatsApp-native formatting (bold, italic, monospace, lists — WhatsApp's subset of markdown). Response length calibration (WhatsApp is a chat app — responses should be short unless the user asks for detail).

10a. **WhatsApp interactive messages** — WhatsApp Business API supports rich message types beyond plain text: reply buttons (up to 3), list messages (up to 10 sections × 10 rows), quick replies, and call-to-action buttons (URL/phone). Design the interaction patterns for core features: TODO completion ("Mark done?" with [Done] [Snooze] [Skip] buttons), reminder confirmation ("Remind you at 3pm?" with [Yes] [Change time] buttons), email preview approval ([Send] [Edit] [Cancel]), calendar event creation ([Confirm] [Change time] [Cancel]). Map each feature's decision points to the appropriate interactive message type. Document the full interaction flow for each feature.

10b. **Error UX** — Every failure mode must send a meaningful WhatsApp message to the user, not silence. Error categories and responses: (1) MiniMax/LLM down → "I'm having trouble thinking right now. I'll try again in a moment." + automatic retry after 30s. (2) Groq/STT down → "I can't process voice notes right now. Could you type that instead?" (3) Rate limited → "You're sending messages faster than I can keep up. Give me a minute." (4) Image processing failed → "I couldn't read that image. Could you try sending it again?" (5) WhatsApp send failed → retry silently up to 3 times, then log for manual review. (6) OpenViking down → degrade gracefully (process without context retrieval, queue messages for later commit). Build `App\Services\ErrorResponseService` mapping exception types to user-friendly WhatsApp messages.

10c. **Privacy policy & ToS** — Required for Meta Business API app review and GDPR compliance. Write a basic but robust privacy policy covering: what data is collected (phone number, messages, media, calendar data), how it's processed (sent to MiniMax, Groq, GLM for AI processing; stored in OpenViking and PostgreSQL), data retention periods, right to erasure (user says "delete my data" → purge OpenViking account + PostgreSQL records + R2 files), data export (user says "export my data" → generate downloadable archive). Host at `https://{domain}/privacy`. ToS covering acceptable use, service availability, no warranty. Keep both concise and readable.

## Tier 2 — Individual Features (Stickiness Priority)

### 2A — TODO Lists + Daily Reminders (highest stickiness)

11. **TODO CRUD via natural language** — User says "add buy groceries to my list" or "todo: call dentist" or sends a voice note about tasks → Navi extracts TODO items, confirms, persists. Storage: OpenViking resources (semantically searchable) + PostgreSQL (`todos` table for structured queries — due dates, priority, completion status). Support multiple lists ("work", "personal", "groceries"). List/view/complete/delete via natural commands ("what's on my list?", "done with groceries", "clear completed").

12. **Daily reminder system** — Scheduled job (Laravel scheduler + Redis queue) that runs at user-configured time (default 8:00 AM local timezone). Queries active TODOs, composes a morning digest, sends via WhatsApp Business API (Message Template for proactive sends outside 24hr window). Smart prioritization: overdue items first, then today's items, then upcoming. Configurable frequency ("remind me every morning", "only on weekdays", "don't remind me on weekends"). Snooze support ("remind me about this later", "push this to tomorrow").

13. **Ad-hoc reminders** — "Remind me to call Maria at 3pm", "remind me about the report on Friday". Time parsing from natural language (handle relative: "in 2 hours", "tomorrow morning", "next Monday"; and absolute: "April 10th at 9am"). Timezone-aware. Persist in PostgreSQL (`reminders` table) with a scheduled job that checks and fires via WhatsApp Business API (Message Template for proactive sends outside 24hr window) at the right time.

### 2B — Scheduling + Calendar Integration

14. **Appointment creation via natural language** — "Schedule a meeting with the team on Thursday at 2pm", "I have a dentist appointment next Tuesday at 10am". Parse event details (title, datetime, duration, location, participants). Store in PostgreSQL (`events` table). Confirm with user before creating.

15. **Google Calendar integration** — OAuth2 flow initiated via WhatsApp ("connect my Google Calendar" → Navi sends auth link → user completes in browser → callback stores tokens in PostgreSQL). Two-way sync: events created in Navi push to Google Calendar; Google Calendar events pulled into Navi's context. Google Meet link generation for meetings. Use Google Calendar API v3. Handle token refresh, scope management, calendar selection.

16. **Schedule-aware reminders** — Morning digest includes today's calendar events alongside TODOs. Pre-event reminders (configurable: 15min, 30min, 1hr before). Conflict detection ("you have a meeting at 2pm, but you also scheduled a dentist appointment at 2:30pm"). Weekly summary option ("here's your week ahead").

### 2C — Note-Taking + Summarization

17. **Note capture from any modality** — Text notes: direct save to OpenViking. Voice notes: Groq Whisper transcribes → MiniMax summarizes → save both transcript and summary as OpenViking resources. Images: GLM-4.7-Flash describes → original file stored (Cloudflare R2) → text description saved as OpenViking resource with relation link to file path. Documents: OpenViking's built-in parser handles PDF/DOCX/HTML natively → save summary + full content. All notes stored in OpenViking as resources with semantic indexing. PostgreSQL `notes` table for metadata (title, created_at, tags, source_type, original_file_path).

18. **Note linking & retrieval** — Automatic linking: OpenViking's semantic search connects related notes ("that restaurant idea I had last week"). Manual tagging via natural language ("tag this as work", "file this under trip planning"). Search via natural language queries ("what did I note about the budget meeting?", "find my notes from March"). OpenViking's L0 abstracts enable fast scanning; L2 detail loaded on demand.

19. **Summarization engine** — On-demand summarization of accumulated notes ("summarize my notes from this week", "what are the key points from my project notes?"). Periodic automatic summaries (weekly digest of all notes). Summarization uses MiniMax M2.5 with OpenViking context retrieval — pulls all relevant notes, generates concise summary, stores summary as a new linked resource.

19a. **Note synthesis & resource compaction** — OpenViking does not auto-compact resources. A user who takes hundreds of notes over months creates retrieval pressure even with semantic search (L0 abstracts accumulate, competing for attention during retrieval). Build a scheduled `SynthesizeNotesJob` that: (1) clusters semantically related notes via OpenViking search, (2) generates a parent summary resource that links to its children via the Relations API, (3) stores the synthesis as a new OpenViking resource with its own L0/L1/L2. The synthesis becomes the preferred retrieval target; children are loaded on demand for drill-down. Run weekly per user via MiniMax M2.5 (same quality tier as all other OpenViking operations — synthesis is lossy compression, quality matters). Track synthesis history in PostgreSQL to avoid re-processing unchanged note clusters.

### 2D — Email Dictation

20. **Email composition via voice/text** — "Send an email to juan@example.com saying I'll be late to the meeting". Parse: recipient, subject (auto-generated or specified), body. Draft preview sent back in WhatsApp for confirmation before sending. Support dictation flow: "new email to Maria" → Navi asks for subject → user dictates body → preview → "send it" / "change the subject" / "add a paragraph about X".

21. **Email sending integration** — SMTP or transactional email service (Resend, matching breakthrough project). OAuth2 for Gmail send-as (user sends from their own address, not Navi's). Store sent email records in PostgreSQL for context. Handle attachments: user sends a document in WhatsApp → "email this to Juan" → document attached to email.

### 2E — Affordance Communication (Critical UX Challenge)

22. **Progressive feature discovery** — The user explicitly called this out: avoid becoming a glorified TODO list by failing to communicate capabilities. Approach: contextual suggestions during natural conversation. If user sends a voice note and Navi transcribes it, mention: "I saved this as a note. I can also set a reminder or add this to your TODO list." First-interaction onboarding flow: brief capability overview via WhatsApp messages. Weekly "did you know?" tips based on unused features. Feature usage tracking in PostgreSQL to drive discovery prompts intelligently (don't suggest what they already use).

## Tier 3 — Network Features (Metcalfe's Law)

### 3A — Cross-User Delegation

23. **Agent-mediated task delegation** — User A: "Ask Luis if he can cover my shift on Thursday." If Luis is a Navi user → Navi DMs Luis directly, negotiates, confirms, updates both users. If Luis is not a user → Navi informs User A and offers to send an invitation link. Delegation state machine in PostgreSQL (`delegations` table: requester, target, task, status, timestamps). Both users' OpenViking contexts updated with delegation outcomes.

24. **Organic viral invitation loop** — Every failed delegation (target not a Navi user) is an invitation moment. Navi sends a WhatsApp message to the target: "[User A] wants to coordinate with you through Navi. [brief value prop]. [signup link]". Track invitation → signup → activation funnel in PostgreSQL. Referral bonuses (extended features, priority reminders) for users whose invitations convert.

### 3B — Multi-Party Scheduling

25. **N-body scheduling** — "Find a time that works for me, Luis, and Maria for lunch this week." If all three are Navi users → query each user's calendar/events → find intersections → propose options → each user confirms via their WhatsApp chat with Navi. Constraint propagation algorithm for finding optimal slots across multiple calendars with preferences (preferred times, lunch vs dinner, travel time).

26. **Group event coordination** — Trip planning, dinner parties, team meetings. One user initiates → Navi creates a coordination session → polls participants for preferences → converges on plan → creates events for all participants. Shared context stored in OpenViking with cross-user relation links.

### 3C — Group Chat Memory (Speculative / Deferred)

27. **WhatsApp group chat integration** — Speculative only. Do not treat as a v1 dependency or design anchor until WhatsApp Business group-chat support is confirmed as real, available, and policy-safe for Navi's account class. If it becomes viable, users add Navi's phone number to WhatsApp group chats and Navi becomes the persistent memory of the group. "What did we decide about the trip?" → Navi searches group conversation history via OpenViking. Configurable: active (responds to queries, participates) vs passive (only responds when mentioned or directly asked). **Multi-session design challenge:** OpenViking sessions are single-user scoped — there is no native multi-user session concept. Design: dedicated OpenViking session per group (for group-level context, decisions, action items) + cross-references to individual user sessions via Relations API. Group commits extract memories into an agent-scoped space (`viking://agent/group-{id}/memories/`), not user-scoped. Individual user memories ("Maria committed to booking the Airbnb") are extracted to the respective user's memory space with a relation back to the group session. Commit frequency must be aggressive — group chats generate high message volume.

28. **Group action item tracking** — Navi automatically detects commitments in group conversation ("I'll bring the wine", "Maria will book the Airbnb"). Tracks who committed to what. Follow-up reminders to individuals via DM ("You mentioned you'd book the Airbnb for the weekend trip — just checking in"). Group accountability without public shaming.

### 3D — Shared Lists & Projects

29. **Collaborative TODO lists** — Shared grocery lists, trip packing lists, project task lists. Any participant can add/complete/remove items via their DM with Navi. Changes broadcast to all participants. Conflict resolution (two people mark the same item done → acknowledge both).

30. **Coordination graph accumulation** — The social coordination graph is the core moat. However, OpenViking's Relations API carries only a `reason` string — no numeric weights, frequency counts, or typed metadata. **Dual-layer approach:** PostgreSQL `coordination_edges` table stores quantitative metrics (user_a, user_b, coordination_count, last_coordinated_at, avg_response_time, reliability_score, topic_tags). OpenViking memories store qualitative patterns ("User A and User B coordinate weekly about groceries, User B typically responds within an hour"). A scheduled `UpdateCoordinationMetricsJob` aggregates delegation outcomes, shared list activity, scheduling interactions, and group chat participation into PostgreSQL edge weights. The LLM reads both sources: structured metrics from PostgreSQL + qualitative patterns from OpenViking memories. Used for: intelligent reminder timing, delegation reliability scoring (internal, never exposed), proactive coordination suggestions ("You and Maria usually plan a weekend outing around this time of month"). This behavioral model is impossible for a new entrant to replicate.

## Tier 4 — Growth, Polish & Monetization

31. **Onboarding optimization** — First-message experience. A/B test different onboarding flows (guided tour vs immediate use vs capability showcase). Measure time-to-first-value (how quickly a new user creates their first TODO/reminder). Optimize for "aha moment" — the point where a user realizes this is more than a chatbot.

32. **Analytics & instrumentation** — User engagement metrics: daily active users, messages per user, feature adoption rates, retention curves. Track per-feature stickiness (which features correlate with long-term retention?). OpenViking usage metrics: memory growth rate, search effectiveness, context retrieval latency. Cost metrics: LLM token consumption per user, per feature, per model.

33. **Monetization strategy** — Freemium model. Free tier: TODO lists, basic reminders, limited notes (rate-limited at 5 msgs/min). Paid tier: calendar integration, email dictation, unlimited notes, higher rate limits. Team/family tier: network features (delegation, multi-party scheduling, group memory, shared lists). Usage-based pricing for high-volume users. WhatsApp Business API conversation costs ($0.005-0.08/conversation) absorbed into tier pricing.

34. **LLM provider runtime failover** — The `ProviderInterface` design enables swapping models, but there's no runtime failover if MiniMax goes down. Build health check + automatic fallback: ping MiniMax before each call (or cache health status with 30s TTL), on failure route to Qwen3.5 Plus ($0.26/$1.56) or GLM-4.7 ($0.60/$2.20) as fallback. Same pattern for Groq (fallback: OpenAI Whisper $0.006/min) and GLM image processing (fallback: Gemini 2.5 Flash-Lite $0.10/$0.40). Configure fallback chain in `config/providers.php`. Log all failovers for cost tracking and reliability monitoring.

35. **Cost alerting** — Build on the `api_usage_records` cost tracking from item #6h. Per-user alerts: if a user's daily LLM cost exceeds 2x their rolling average, flag for review (possible abuse or runaway loop). System-wide alerts: if total daily cost exceeds configurable threshold, notify admin via WhatsApp (meta — Navi monitoring itself). Integrate with Sentry for anomaly detection. Dashboard view for cost breakdown by user, feature, model, operation type.

36. **Multi-language support** — Spanish first (matching breakthrough project's i18n infrastructure). System prompts, onboarding messages, error messages, feature discovery tips all localized. OpenViking handles multilingual content natively (semantic search works across languages). Follow breakthrough project's i18n conventions: JSON locale files, `trans()` calls, CI key parity checks.

